In Java, the `==` operator is indeed commonly used for comparing strings. However, using `==` to compare strings is not always appropriate, especially for custom string comparison logic. Here are some key points to understand when and why you should use the `==` operator or `.equals()` for string comparison:

### `==` Operator
- **String Comparison**: The `==` operator is used to compare the values of two strings to check if they are the same at a specific point in time. This means it compares the actual characters and byte values of the strings.
- **Usage**: It is useful when you want to determine if two strings refer to the same object in memory.
    ```java
    String str1 = "Hello";
    String str2 = "Hello";
    if (str1 == str2) {
        System.out.println("The strings are the same.");
    }
    ```
- **Example**:
      ```java
      String s1 = "Hello";
      String s2 = new String("Hello");
      String s3 = "Goodbye";
      System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true (at a specific point in time)
      System.out.println(s1 == s3); // false (different characters)
      ```

### `.equals()` Method
- **Custom Comparison**: If you need to compare two strings based on custom logic, you should use the `.equals()` method instead of `==`.
- **Custom Logic**: `.equals()` allows you to define your own custom comparison logic. This is useful if you have specific rules or custom comparison criteria for your strings.
    ```java
    public class CustomStringComparator {
        private String string1;
        private String string2;

        public CustomStringComparator(String string1, String string2) {
            this.string1 = string1;
            this.string2 = string2;
        }

        public boolean equals(Object obj) {
            if (this == obj) return true;
            if (obj == null || getClass()!= obj.getClass()) return false;
            return string1.equals(string2);
        }

        public boolean equalsIgnoreCase(String str) {
            if (this == str) return true;
            if (str == null || getClass()!= str.getClass()) return false;
            return String.equals(this, str);
        }
    }

    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            CustomStringComparator custom = new CustomStringComparator("Hello", "Hello");
            System.out.println(custom.string1.equals(custom.string2)); // true
            System.out.println(custom.string1.equals("Goodbye")); // false
        }
    }
    ```
